Creating a sonnet with vivid imagery and evocative language in C# involves leveraging string manipulation and randomization to craft poetic lines. Below is an example of how you might achieve this programmatically:

```csharp
using System;

class SonnetGenerator
{
    static void Main()
    {
        string[] subjects = { "Stars", "Moon", "Galaxy", "Comets", "Nebula" };
        string[] verbs = { "whisper", "glow", "dance", "sparkle", "paint" };
        string[] adjectives = { "majestic", "ethereal", "celestial", "luminous", "silent" };
        string[] nouns = { "night", "cosmos", "sky", "void", "dreams" };
        string[] sensoryDetails = { "twinkling lights", "silent whispers", "endless darkness", "silver glow", "celestial wonders" };

        Random rand = new Random();

        string line1 = $"{subjects[rand.Next(subjects.Length)]} {verbs[rand.Next(verbs.Length)]} in {adjectives[rand.Next(adjectives.Length)]} {nouns[rand.Next(nouns.Length)]}";
        string line2 = $"{adjectives[rand.Next(adjectives.Length)]} {sensoryDetails[rand.Next(sensoryDetails.Length)]}, {verbs[rand.Next(verbs.Length)]} on high";
        string line3 = $"{nouns[rand.Next(nouns.Length)]} holds secrets, {verbs[rand.Next(verbs.Length)]} from afar";
        string line4 = $"In {adjectives[rand.Next(adjectives.Length)]} {nouns[rand.Next(nouns.Length)]}, we gaze, we sigh";

        Console.WriteLine("Sonnet:");
        Console.WriteLine(line1);
        Console.WriteLine(line2);
        Console.WriteLine(line3);
        Console.WriteLine(line4);
    }
}
```

This program randomly selects words from predefined arrays to create a short and vivid sonnet. You can expand the arrays with more descriptive words to enhance the richness of the poem. The sonnet is kept concise to stay within the 50-word limit.
